item.content:encoded:
Every company has some kind of values. Most are a collection of inspirational attributes. Like "<a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2002/01/19/opinion/enron-s-vision-and-values-thing.html">Communication. Respect. Integrity. Excellence.</a>" They are very similar to those inspirational quotes that you read very often in your Facebook feed: They make you feel warm and fuzzy ... and then you move on and go about your day.

Values are meaningless if not put into action.&nbsp;

In the end it needs to become stories to be real.&nbsp;

Culture is velocity.&nbsp;

We did the exercise that I'm quite proud of.&nbsp;

Meetings have a bad reputation. Asking friends and colleagues what the favourite part of their job is, meetings will definitely score fairly low on that list. However, somehow we don't manage to get rid of them. Rather than trying to fix meetings by running them better (have an agenda, outcomes, clear roles, ...), let use Peter Drucker's quote as a starting point:
<blockquote>There is nothing quite so useless as doing with great efficiency something that should not be done at all.</blockquote>
The goal of any meeting should be to coordinate work, collaborate towards a result or share information. The meeting should be seen only as one of many tools in the toolkit of a well-functioning tema. A lot of meetings can be substituted by asynchronous forms of communication such as email or slack channels. They have the benefit that everybody involved can work in their own time which takes away the pain of coordinating time.&nbsp;

However, I would argue that there are four meetings that benefit from being held synchronously. At least they have helped me in the past a great deal.&nbsp;
<h3>Daily standups</h3>
Once a day, preferrably in the morning, no more than 15 minutes, where all team members provide an update on three topics:&nbsp;
<ol>
	<li>What did I accomplish yesterday?&nbsp;</li>
	<li>What is on my plate for today (and what meetings)?</li>
	<li>Do we need to re-balance some commitments (i.e. flag delays) or schedule time to discuss content for anything?&nbsp;</li>
</ol>
In my experience, daily standups work best when they focus exclusively on process and not diverge into content discussion, since that has the potential to derail the conversation by chasing down bunny trails and suddenly hijacking everybody's time. However, daily standups are an excellent opportunity to identify the content topics that you need to discuss in separate meetings and who should be involved.&nbsp;

Keep it to maximum 15 minutes should keep everybody on track and make sure that no one dominates the meeting – and that only works if you don't dive into content. Adjust as necessary, but I'd argue that the only hard rule is: "no content". That's all. Not rocket science, but a good vegetable to keep the team healthy. As usual the <a href="https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stand-up_meeting">Wikipedia entry on Daily Standups</a> provides some good further reading and links.&nbsp;
<h3>Weekly 1:1s</h3>
In my experience, it is less important what you discuss in a 1:1, but more important that you have them: Weekly, with every one of your direct reports, 30 minutes, no matter what. The agenda should not be set by you, but by your direct reports. Talk about whatever they want to talk about most. Use the time to better understand the individuals, figure out what moves them and how you can best help them to be successful.&nbsp;

I've had lots of situations where people that are not used to 1:1s doubt them initially or offer to cancel them when your workload increases. Don't take that unintended bait, but lean in. The 1:1 is your best chance to maintain the connection with your team and help each other understand what going on – especially in stressful times.&nbsp;

Rather than going into the details of how to conduct a 1:1, I leave you with the most important message: Do them. Weekly, 30 minutes, no matter what. If you want to know more, have a look at Michael Lopp's excellent write-up of the topic: <a href="http://randsinrepose.com/archives/the-update-the-vent-and-the-disaster/">The Update, the Vent and the Disaster</a>. More than six years old, still as good and relevant as new.
<h3>Monthly Professional Development conversations</h3>
Looking back at my professional journey, the moments when I have been most engaged where the ones when I developed most and when I felt someone took interest in my professional development. In the same way, the more I took interest in my team's individual development, the more engaged they were. It's basically one of those situations where everybody wins: The team gets better, and the better the team gets, the better the results.&nbsp;

So, once a month, set aside some time to discuss professional development. Provide feedback on what works well and how to improve, set goals and review them on a regular basis. I typically prepare some notes beforehand based on my observations over past the month and share them with the person. Yes, it takes some time and effort to do this, but it pays off.&nbsp;

If you do it well, at some point you are talking about going different. Take it up to the point, where people are talking about parting ways to take the next step. And that is more than OK. There is a good presentation by <a href="https://youtu.be/yBo0Y8OSGLE">Mike Monteiro on The is the golden age of design ... and we're screwed</a>, who talks about the seamstress model. At the end of the apprenticeship is ready to go out into the world to build an own business. It is the role of the senior seamstress to prepare her for that, including building a client base to start from.&nbsp;
<h3>Weekly team meetings</h3>
This is the one I'm most ambiguous about, but so far my experience is that it helps the team more than it costs. This meeting can be anywhere from 30 to 60 minutes and should set the tone and plan for the week ahead. It is an opportunity to get everyone on the same page and have some room for content discussion with the team. While the daily standup are a good way to manage the runway, weekly team meetings take care of the 10,000 ft horizon and make sure that people are aware of the bigger topics that are going on. A good starting point is the following agenda:
<ul>
	<li>What’s going on, what do we care about, What were last week's highlights?</li>
	<li>How are we tracking on critical metrics?</li>
	<li>Have a debate around one or maximum two big topics at the moment</li>
</ul>
<ol>
	<li>Weekly 1:1s</li>
	<li>Monthly professional development chats</li>
</ol>
Other meetings should be held only on an as-needed basis.
